<subSubSection id="C34065587A3CFFADFCB507C83608B57C" lastPageId="19" lastPageNumber="248" pageId="18" pageNumber="247" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BE536D37A3CFFADFCB507C83608B57C" blockId="18.[828,1437,1760,2071]" lastBlockId="19.[151,761,190,757]" lastPageId="19" lastPageNumber="248" pageId="18" pageNumber="247">
<emphasis id="B92EEAC17A3CFFACFCB507C83004B1FE" bold="true" box="[828,1077,1760,1783]" pageId="18" pageNumber="247">
Redescription. 
<emphasis id="B92EEAC17A3CFFACFC7307C83004B1FE" bold="true" box="[1018,1077,1760,1783]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="247">Body</emphasis>
</emphasis>
length 1.7–2.0 mm (
<typeStatus id="54E188717A3CFFACFABF07C831ADB1FE" box="[1334,1436,1760,1783]" pageId="18" pageNumber="247">holotype</typeStatus>
<quantity id="4CA29B367A3CFFACFCB5062837A5B01E" box="[828,916,1792,1815]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="18" pageNumber="247" unit="mm" value="1.8">1.8 mm</quantity>
), maximum body width 1.0– 
<quantity id="4CA29B367A3CFFACFB5E0628311DB01E" box="[1239,1324,1792,1815]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="18" pageNumber="247" unit="mm" value="1.2">1.2 mm</quantity>
(
<typeStatus id="54E188717A3CFFACFAB4062831ADB01E" box="[1341,1436,1792,1815]" pageId="18" pageNumber="247">holotype</typeStatus>
1.0 mm). Head and labrum black; pronotum uniformly yellowish or brown centrally and gradually getting paler towards margins; elytra uniformly yellowish to pale brown, with slightly darkened striae; legs yellowish. 
<emphasis id="B92EEAC17A3CFFACFA8506A83176B09E" bold="true" box="[1292,1351,1920,1943]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="247">Head</emphasis>
without microsculpture on interstices; punctation sparse, each puncture bearing yellowish pointed seta. Eyes separated by 3.1× the width of one eye in dorsal view. 
<emphasis id="B92EEAC17A3CFFACFAA406C831ADB0FE" bold="true" box="[1325,1436,2016,2039]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="247">Pronotum</emphasis>
with sparse setiferous punctation similar to that on head; interstices without microsculpture. 
<emphasis id="B92EEAC17A3DFFADFD9C01963668B7DC" bold="true" box="[533,601,190,213]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="248">Elytra</emphasis>
with 10 striae sharply impressed except anteromedially (near scutellar shield) where neither striae nor serial punctures are visible; intervals weakly convex at midlength and near apex; interval punctation sparse, setiferous; interstices without microsculpture. 
<emphasis id="B92EEAC17A3DFFADFEDB007635F0B67C" bold="true" box="[338,449,350,373]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="248">Aedeagus</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="13612A567A3DFFADFE5D0076362FB67C" box="[468,542,350,373]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="18.[151,182,1467,1486]" captionTargetBox="[178,1432,202,1437]" captionTargetId="figure-13@18.[151,1436,186,1450]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Fig. 9. Male genitalia of Thysanarthria species, holotypes. A–E – T. saurahana sp. nov. (A–C – whole aedeagus in dorsal, lateral and ventral view; D–E – detail of median lobe and parameres in dorsal and ventral view). F–J – T. siamensis Hebauer, 2001 (F–H – whole aedeagus in dorsal, lateral and ventral view; I–J – details of parameres and median lobe in dorsal and ventral view)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4488942" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4488942/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="248">Figs 9</figureCitation>
F–J) 
<quantity id="4CA29B367A3DFFADFDD500763685B67C" box="[604,692,350,373]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="19" pageNumber="248" unit="mm" value="0.7">0.7 mm</quantity>
long. Phallobase widened in apical half, widest shortly below bases of parameres (slightly wider than parameres combined); weakly arcuate in lateral view. Parameres short, narrowly elongate, constricted at midlength, widened into rounded lobes apically; widely triangular in lateral view. Median lobe narrow, shorter than parameres, sharply pointed, without membranous apex of paired subapical lobes; gonopore circular, situated subapically.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34065587A3DFFADFF1E035636DCB5FC" pageId="19" pageNumber="248" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BE536D37A3DFFADFF1E035636DCB5FC" blockId="19.[151,761,190,757]" pageId="19" pageNumber="248">
<emphasis id="B92EEAC17A3DFFADFF1E035635A5B59C" bold="true" box="[151,404,638,661]" pageId="19" pageNumber="248">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C5A4D507A3DFFADFE1503563694B59C" authorityName="Hebauer" authorityYear="2001" box="[412,677,638,661]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Thysanarthria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="siamensis">
<emphasis id="B92EEAC17A3DFFADFE1503563694B59C" box="[412,677,638,661]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="248">Thysanarthria siamensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very characteristic by a relatively large aedeagus with lanceolate parameres and sharply pointed median lobe and is hence hard to be confused with any other species of the genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34065587A3DFFADFCB5019630F2B61C" pageId="19" pageNumber="248" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8BE536D37A3DFFADFCB5019630F2B61C" blockId="19.[828,1437,190,341]" pageId="19" pageNumber="248">
<emphasis id="B92EEAC17A3DFFADFCB5019637A7B7DC" bold="true" box="[828,918,190,213]" pageId="19" pageNumber="248">Biology.</emphasis>
Specimens from 
<collectingCountry id="F34D76437A3DFFADFBC0019630B2B7DC" box="[1097,1155,190,213]" name="India" pageId="19" pageNumber="248">India</collectingCountry>
: Uttarkhand were collected at the sides of small to large stony rivers, microhabitat is unknown (M. A. Jäch, pers. comm.).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34065587A3DFFADFCB5003631ACB65C" pageId="19" pageNumber="248" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BE536D37A3DFFADFCB5003631ACB65C" blockId="19.[828,1437,190,341]" pageId="19" pageNumber="248">
<emphasis id="B92EEAC17A3DFFADFCB5003637FEB63C" bold="true" box="[828,975,286,309]" pageId="19" pageNumber="248">Distribution.</emphasis>
The species is widespread, ranging from western Himalaya to central 
<collectingCountry id="F34D76437A3DFFADFBE7001630FCB65C" box="[1134,1229,318,341]" name="Thailand" pageId="19" pageNumber="248">Thailand</collectingCountry>
and northern 
<collectingCountry id="F34D76437A3DFFADFAE8001631A9B65C" box="[1377,1432,318,341]" name="Laos" pageId="19" pageNumber="248">Laos</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
